 B: diag() 
 C: propo() 
 D: matrix()

 save.png()

What is the right way to use ifelse() in R? 
 
 A: The first argument is your if logical, the second argument your else, there is no other argument. 
 B: The first argument is your logical, the second what should happen if it is true, the third if it is false. 
 C: The first argument is the logical to test, the other arguments allow you to make several outcomes. 
 D: ifelse() is the same as three if-else statements.

What is the function of %>%? 
 
 A: It transmits the value from one line into the function in the next line. 
 B: It transforms the value using a single function on the left hand side and assigns it to the variable on the right hand side. 
 C: It assigns a value to a variable name. 
 D: It allows you to combine elements of the ggplot package.

Which of the following is impossible in R? 
 
 A: Making memes. 
 B: Loading current data from a URL. 
 C: Creating an app that organizes your spreadsheet. 
 D: None of the above.

Which of these is not a real difference between R and Python? 
 
 A: A global variable can be called within a function in one but not the other language. 
 B: The indexing begins with 0 in one of them, with 1 in the other. 
 C: Square brackets [] cannot be used to access elements in a data frame in one of them. 
 D: One of them relies more heavily on libraries than the other to perform its primary functions.

Which one of these gives you a quick overview of some of your data from a data frame? 
 
 A: View(df) 
 B: get_overview(df) 
 C: tidyr::look(df) 
  D: head(df)

 B: ggplot() + geom_count(mapping = c(x = xvar, y = yvar)) 
 C: ggplot(data = data, mapping = aes(x = xvar"
